<figure class="crisis-lens">
  <figcaption>Sovereign-debt crisis logic (Lecture 10): beliefs, pricing, and repayment capacity</figcaption>
  <div class="crisis-lens-grid">
    <article>
      <h3>1) Pricing</h3>
      <p>Investors require a higher gross return when default probability rises.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><code>(1 - pi^def) R = R'</code></li>
      </ul>
    </article>
    <article>
      <h3>2) Repayment Risk</h3>
      <p>Default probability rises when required repayment <code>R D</code> is high relative to uncertain tax capacity.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><code>pi^def = F(R D)</code></li>
      </ul>
    </article>
    <article>
      <h3>3) Feedback</h3>
      <p>Higher <code>pi^def</code> implies higher <code>R</code>, which raises <code>R D</code>, which can raise <code>pi^def</code> again.</p>
    </article>
    <article>
      <h3>4) Outcomes</h3>
      <p>Multiple equilibria can exist: a low-risk equilibrium, a fragile high-risk equilibrium, and a market freeze outcome.</p>
    </article>
  </div>
</figure>
